**Story‑line reading of the lyrics**

| Japanese line (literal feel) | What it suggests in a fantastical, “literal‑in‑the‑world” reading |
|------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------|
| **ドングリを辿っても着きません**<br>*Even if you follow the trail of acorns you never arrive* | The restaurant is hidden behind a magical barrier that can only be crossed by those who have *lost* something essential (memory, purpose, or a physical token). Simply following a natural sign (the acorns) is not enough. |
| **森の小さなレストラン**<br>*The tiny restaurant in the forest* | A secluded, other‑worldly eatery that exists deep in the woods, invisible to ordinary humans. |
| **空っぽのポケットを弄って**<br>*Fiddling with empty pockets* | Patrons arrive with nothing to pay – they have no money, no belongings, no worldly ties. |
| **忘れた人から辿り着く**<br>*You reach it from the person who forgot* | The way in is opened by someone who has forgotten (e.g., a lost soul, an amnesiac, or a spirit that has let go of its former life). |
| **予約は一つもありません**<br>*No reservations at all* | The place does not take bookings; it appears only when the right condition (forgetting) is met. |
| **空席だらけのランチ時**<br>*The lunch hour is full of empty seats* | The dining room is always vacant because only a few spirits come at a time; the emptiness itself is part of the atmosphere. |
| **小鳥がパタパタ笑ってる**<br>*Small birds are flutter‑laughing* | The birds are not ordinary birds; they are tiny spirit‑messengers or guardians who giggle as they watch the strange clientele. |
| **真っ赤なペンキのトタン屋根**<br>*A tin roof painted bright red* | A vivid, almost theatrical marker that signals the boundary between the mundane forest and the other‑worldly diner. |
| **メニューはおすすめ そればかり**<br>*The menu is only the “recommended” dish* | There is no choice; everyone receives the same set meal – the “final course” appropriate for their transition. |
| **厨房の方から聞こえてる<br>バイオリン フルート チェロ ビオラ**<br>*From the kitchen you hear violin, flute, cello, viola* | The kitchen is staffed by musicians‑spirits; the music is part of the ritual that prepares the soul for departure. |
| **ようこそようこそ いらっしゃい**<br>*Welcome, welcome, please come in* | The greeting is extended to any wandering spirit that has managed to cross the threshold. |
| **たらふく食べたらお眠りよ**<br>*Eat your fill, then go to sleep* | Consuming the meal induces a peaceful slumber – a metaphor for the soul’s release from the body. |
| **それでは皆さんさようなら**<br>*Well then, everybody, goodbye* | After the meal and sleep, the patrons depart, having completed their visit. |
| **明日は明日で エトセトラ**<br>*Tomorrow is tomorrow, etc.* | The cycle repeats; each day brings a new set of forgotten souls to the restaurant. |
| **右から左へおおわらわ**<br>*A great commotion from right to left* | The normal order of things is inverted – a sign that the usual laws of cause‑and‑effect do not apply here. |
| **手乗りの子熊も踊り出す**<br>*Even the hand‑sized bear cub starts to dance* | The forest’s infant inhabitants (spirit‑bears) join the celebration, showing that even the youngest beings partake in the rite. |
| **カルパッチョ パエリア オードブル<br>リゾット デザートはありません**<br>*Carpaccio, paella, hors d’oeuvres, risotto – no dessert* | The set menu is a lavish, multicourse feast, but there is no sweet finish – the “dessert” would represent lingering attachment, which is deliberately omitted. |
| **お墓の中まで届けましょう**<br>*Let’s deliver it even to the inside of the grave* | The food (or its spiritual essence) is carried beyond the restaurant, all the way to the burial place, as an offering to the deceased. |
| **今宵は最後のフルコース**<br>*Tonight is the last full course* | The evening’s meal is the final, decisive nourishment that prepares the soul for its onward journey. |

